{"title_page": "Christiansen", "text_new": "__NOTOC__\n'''Christiansen''' ({{IPA-da|k\u02b0\u0281e\u02c8stj\u00e6n\u02c0sn\u0329}}) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] and [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[patronymic]] [[surname]], literally meaning ''son of Christian''. The spelling variant '''Kristiansen''' has  identical pronunciation. Christiansen is the sixteenth most common name in [[Denmark]], but is shared by less than 1% of the population.<ref>[http://www.dst.dk/Statistik/Navne/pop/2007.aspx Navne TOP-20 for hele Danmarks befolkning pr. 1. januar 2007 - Danmarks Statistik<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012023436/http://www.dst.dk/Statistik/Navne/pop/2007.aspx |date=October 12, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe numbers of bearers of the surnames Christiansen and Kristiansen in [[Denmark]] and [[Norway]] (2007):\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!\n!Christiansen\n!Kristiansen\n!source\n|-\n|Denmark\n|align=\"right\"|39112\n|align=\"right\"|14248\n|[http://www.dst.dk/Statistik/Navne/HvorMange.aspx Statistics Denmark]\n|-\n|Norway\n|align=\"right\"|3922\n|align=\"right\"|24533\n|[http://www.ssb.no/navn/ Statistics Norway]\n|}\n\nImmigrants to [[English language|English]]-speaking countries sometimes have changed the spelling to [[Christianson]] or [[Kristianson]].\n==Persons==\n'''Christiansen''', as a person, may refer to:\n===A===\n*[[Anders Baasmo Christiansen]] (born 1976-), Norwegian actor\n*[[Arthur Christiansen]] (1904\u20131963), English journalist\n===B===\n*[[Barbara Christiansen]], Cruelty Investigator\n*[[Bjarne Slot Christiansen]] (born 1952), Danish team builder\n\n===C===\n*[[Carl Emil Christiansen]] (1937\u20132018), Danish footballer\n*[[Carlos Christiansen]] (born 1985), Peruvian, Human Resources expert, entrepreneur, Bitcoins Latin America leader\n*[[Christian Christiansen]] (1843\u20131917), Danish physicist\n*[[Claus Christiansen (footballer, born 1967)]], Danish football defender\n*[[Claus Christiansen (footballer, born 1972)]], Danish footballer and manager\n*[[Clay Christiansen]] (born 1958), American organist\n\n===D===\n*[[Dorte Christiansen]], Danish cricketer\n===E===\n*[[Erik Christiansen]] (born 1956), Danish rower\n===F===\n*[[Fredrik Melius Christiansen]] (1871\u20131955), Norwegian violinist and choral conductor\n*[[Friedrich Christiansen]] (1879-1972), German World War I ace and Supreme Commander of the Wehrmacht in the Netherlands 1940-1945\n\n===G===\n*Gerhardt Kirk Christiansen, Danish sole proprietor\n*[[Godtfred Kirk Christiansen]] (1920\u20131995), Danish businessman\n*{{ill|Gregers Julius Christiansen Sr.|dk}}, (1878-1965), Danish Well borer\n\n===I===\n*[[Isobel Christiansen]] (born 1991), English footballer\n*[[Ivette Christiansen]] (born 1969), Peruvian travel agent, mother and women's rights fighter\n===J===\n*[[Jack Christiansen]] (1928\u20131986), American football player and coach\n*[[Jaime Olaf Christiansen]] (born 1989), Peruvian psychologist, Community relations advisor, AIESEC alumnus, coach and global citizen\n*[[Jason Christiansen]] (born 1969), American baseball player\n*[[Jesper Christiansen]] (born 1978), Danish footballer\n*[[Johannes Christiansen|Johannes Christiansen (I)]] (1850\u20131913), Norwegian politician\n*Johannes Christiansen (II), Danish sole proprietor\n\n===K===\n*[[Kaj Christiansen]] (1921\u20132008), Danish footballer and coach\n*Karl Georg Kirk Christiansen, Danish head of the plastic divisions\n*[[Keith Christiansen]] (born 1944), American Olympian and ice hokey player\n*[[Kerry Ann Christiansen]], British actress\n*[[Kim Christiansen]] (born 1976), Norwegian Olympian and snowboarder\n\n===L===\n*[[Larry Christiansen]] (born 1956), American chess grandmaster\n*[[Lauritz Christiansen (sailor)]] (1867\u20131930), Norwegian Olympian and sailor\n*[[Lauritz Christiansen (athlete)]] (1892\u20131976), Danish long-distance runner\n*[[Lisa Christiansen]], Canadian radio personality\n\n===M===\n*[[Margrethe Christiansen]] (1895\u20131971), Danish folk high school teacher\n*[[Marianne Christiansen]] (born 1963), Danish bishop\n*[[Matias Christiansen]] (born 1986), Peruvian aeronautical engineer and academic\n*[[Michael Christiansen]] (1926 or 1927\u20141984),  British newspaper editor\n*[[Michele Christiansen]] (born 1970), American state appeals judge\n*[[Mogens Christiansen]] (born 1972), Danish cricketer\n\n===N===\n*[[Nina Christiansen]] (born 1964), Danish long-distance runner\n===O===\n*[[Ole Kirk Christiansen]] (1891\u20131958),  Danish carpenter and toy maker\n===P===\n*[[Peter Christiansen (footballer, born 1975)]], Danish footballer\n*[[Peter Christiansen (footballer, born 1999)]], Danish footballer\n===R===\n*[[Ragnar Christiansen]] (born 1922), Norwegian politician\n*[[Reggie Christiansen]] (born 1975), American college baseball coach\n*[[Rob Christiansen]], American musician\n*[[Rune Christiansen]] (born 1963), Norwegian poet and novelist\n*[[Rupert Christiansen]] (born 1954), English writer, journalist and critic\n\n===S===\n*[[Sabine Christiansen]] (born 1957), German journalist\n*[[Sonja Boehmer-Christiansen]] (born 1942), English academic\n*[[Sophie Christiansen]] (born 1987), British Paralympian in equestrian events\n\n===T===\n*[[Tanya Christiansen]], American mathematician\n*[[Thomas Christiansen]] (born 1973), Spanish footballer\n*[[Thor Nis Christiansen]] (1957\u20131981), American criminal\n*[[Trine Christiansen]], Danish cricketer\n\n===W===\n*[[Wilbur Norman Christiansen]] (1913\u20132007), Australian radio astronomer\n==Other==\n'''Christiansen''' may also refer to:\n\n*[[Christiansen effect]], a filtering effect\n*[[Christiansen filter]], narrow bandpass or monochromatic optical filter\n*[[Christiansen Academy]], private boarding school in Rubio, T\u00e1chira, Venezuela\n\n==See also==\n*[[Christensen (surname)|Christensen]]\n*[[Christianson]]\n*[[Kristiansen]]\n\n;References\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{surname}}\n\n[[Category:Danish-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Norwegian-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Patronymic surnames]]\n", "text_old": "__NOTOC__\n'''Christiansen''' ({{IPA-da|k\u02b0\u0281\u025b\u02c8stj\u00e6n\u02c0sn\u0329}}) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] and [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[patronymic]] [[surname]], literally meaning ''son of Christian''. The spelling variant '''Kristiansen''' has  identical pronunciation. Christiansen is the sixteenth most common name in [[Denmark]], but is shared by less than 1% of the population.<ref>[http://www.dst.dk/Statistik/Navne/pop/2007.aspx Navne TOP-20 for hele Danmarks befolkning pr. 1. januar 2007 - Danmarks Statistik<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012023436/http://www.dst.dk/Statistik/Navne/pop/2007.aspx |date=October 12, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe numbers of bearers of the surnames Christiansen and Kristiansen in [[Denmark]] and [[Norway]] (2007):\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!\n!Christiansen\n!Kristiansen\n!source\n|-\n|Denmark\n|align=\"right\"|39112\n|align=\"right\"|14248\n|[http://www.dst.dk/Statistik/Navne/HvorMange.aspx Statistics Denmark]\n|-\n|Norway\n|align=\"right\"|3922\n|align=\"right\"|24533\n|[http://www.ssb.no/navn/ Statistics Norway]\n|}\n\nImmigrants to [[English language|English]]-speaking countries sometimes have changed the spelling to [[Christianson]] or [[Kristianson]].\n==Persons==\n'''Christiansen''', as a person, may refer to:\n===A===\n*[[Anders Baasmo Christiansen]] (born 1976-), Norwegian actor\n*[[Arthur Christiansen]] (1904\u20131963), English journalist\n===B===\n*[[Barbara Christiansen]], Cruelty Investigator\n*[[Bjarne Slot Christiansen]] (born 1952), Danish team builder\n\n===C===\n*[[Carl Emil Christiansen]] (1937\u20132018), Danish footballer\n*[[Carlos Christiansen]] (born 1985), Peruvian, Human Resources expert, entrepreneur, Bitcoins Latin America leader\n*[[Christian Christiansen]] (1843\u20131917), Danish physicist\n*[[Claus Christiansen (footballer, born 1967)]], Danish football defender\n*[[Claus Christiansen (footballer, bor